\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
production possibilities frontier
\series default
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 shows the possible production of combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 It is never concave down.
 The 
\series bold
opportunity cost
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Production efficiency
\series default
 means that we are on the PPF.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Allocative efficiency
\series default
 means in addition that we produce the goods that provide the greatest possible
 benefit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
marginal cost
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the slope of the PPF.
 The 
\series bold
marginal benefit
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the increase in utility from another 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, measured in 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
marginal benefit curve
\series default
 specifies marginal benefit and generally goes down (the 
\series bold
principle of decreasing marginal benefit
\series default
).
 At the point of allocative efficiency, the marginal cost and marginal benefit
 are equal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Economic growth
\series default
 expands the PPF and comes in the forms of 
\series bold
technology
\series default
 and 
\series bold
capital accumulation
\series default
.
\end_layout

