\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Gross domestic product
\series default
 is the total market value of the final goods and services produced in a
 country in a time period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
final good
\series default
 is bought by its final user, whereas an 
\series bold
intermediate good
\series default
 is used to make another good.
 Intermediate goods aren't in GDP because that's double counting.
 Final/intermediate sometimes depends on context.
 Financial instruments and secondhand goods are not part of GDP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Real GDP
\series default
 has prices adjusted for a fixed reference year.
 
\series bold
Nominal GDP
\series default
 is not real.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Real GDP per person
\series default
 is a useful metric.
 
\series bold
Potential GDP
\series default
 is the maximum real GDP that can be obtained without shortages of the factors
 of production (inflation comes with that).
 The 
\series bold
Lucas wedge
\series default
 illustrates the cost of a slowdown in productivity growth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
business cycle
\series default
 is an irregular periodic cycle of 
\series bold
expansion
\series default
 and 
\series bold
recession
\series default
 with turning points at the 
\series bold
peak
\series default
 and 
\series bold
trough
\series default
.
 Recessions last at least two quarters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To compare GDPs between different countries, can be more accurate to use
 
\series bold
