\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effect of government
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
budget surplus
\series default
 increases the supply, which decreases the interest rate and the private
 supply (
\series bold
PSLF
\series default
) and increases private demand (
\series bold
PDLF
\series default
).
 A 
\series bold
budget deficit
\series default
 increases the demand, which increases the interest rate and the amount
 of private supply but decreases private demand (the 
\series bold
crowding-out effect
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Ricardo-Barro effect
\series default
 says that government budget doesn't actually affect the interest rate,
 because rational taxpayers save more.
 Most economists find this interesting but extreme.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Money (ch24)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Money
\series default
 is a 
\series bold
means of payment
\series default
 and a 
\series bold
medium of exchange
\series default
 that overcomes the requirement for a 
\series bold
double coincidence of wants
\series default
 as occurs in 
\series bold
barter
\series default
.
 It's also a 
\series bold
unit of account
\series default
 (unit of measurement for prices) and a 
\series bold
store of value
\series default
.
 Money today is mostly in the form of 
\series bold
currency
\series default
 and 
\series bold
deposits
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Canada has two measures of money: 
\series bold
M1
\series default
, which includes currency and chequable deposits and 
\series bold
M2
\series default
 which additionally includes non-chequable deposits and fixed term deposits.
 Stuff the government owns is not considered money.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stuff that 
\series bold
isn't money
\series default
 by our definition: cheques, credit cards.
 They're just means of payment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Depository institutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three depository institutions make up Canada's money: 
\series bold
chartered banks
\series default
 such as RBC, CIBC, and BMO; 
\series bold
credit unions
\series default
, and 
\series bold
trust/mortgage loan companies
\series default
.
 We will call all these things 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

banks
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chartered banks use their funds for four types of assets: 
\series bold
reserves
\series default
 of about 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5-1\%$
\end_inset

, 
\series bold
liquid assets
\series default
 such as treasury bills, 
\series bold
securities
\series default
 such as bonds, and 
\series bold
loans
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Banks provide these benefits:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Create liquidity
\series default
: they borrow short and lend long
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Pool risk
\series default
: one default doesn't have that big of an effect
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Lower cost of borrowing
\series default
: by acting as a central counterparty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Lower cost of monitoring borrowers
\series default
: by doing it efficiently
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is all 
\series bold
fractional reserve banking
\series default
, which is riskier but don't worry, 
\series bold
Basel III
\series default
 will keep it from going that badly so we don't need 
\series bold
100 percent reserve banking
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Financial innovation
\series default
 is when banks create things like variable-rate mortgages and sell mortgage-back
ed securities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Bank of Canada
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is our 
\series bold
central bank
\series default
; it acts as a bank to banks and the government; it is a 
\series bold
lender of last resort
\series default
, and it is the 
\series bold
sole issuer of bank notes
\series default
.
 It owns two assets: Treasury bills, and loans to depository institutions
 (in times of crisis).
 It has two liabilities: Bank of Canada notes (dollar bills!) and depository
 institution deposits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our 
\series bold
monetary base
\series default
 is made up of the Bank of Canada's liabilities and the coins issued by
 the Royal Canadian Mint.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\series bold
open market operation
\series default
 is when the Bank of Canada trades government securities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
bank rate
\series default
 is the interest rate that the Bank of Canada charges for short-term loans
 — it anchors other short-term interest rates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Creating money
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Banks create money by making loans.
 This created money is limited by the monetary base, and further limited
 by the bank's 
\series bold
desired reserves
\series default
 (reserves that it plans to hold) and the 
\series bold
desired currency holding
\series default
.
 The 
\series bold
currency drain 
\series default
ratio
\series bold
 
\series default
is the ratio of currency to deposits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The banking system creates money as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The monetary base is increased.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Bank reserves are increased, creating excess reserves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Banks lend out their excess reserves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The quantity of money increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
New deposits are used to make payments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Some money is lost through currency drain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The increase in deposits increase desired reserves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Banks have less excess reserves than before.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
money multiplier
\series default
 is the amount of money created by a change in the monetary base.
 In Canada, the M1 multiplier has ranged from 
\begin_inset Formula $5.5-10.4$
\end_inset

 and the M2 multiplier has ranged from 
\begin_inset Formula $16-19.5$
\end_inset

.
 It is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
mm & =M/MB\\
 & =(D+C)/(R+C)\\
 & =(1+C/D)/(R/D+C/D)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the amount of money, 
\begin_inset Formula $MB$
\end_inset

 is the monetary base, 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is deposits, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is currency, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is bank reserves.
 (This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $C/D$
\end_inset

 is the currency drain ratio and 
\begin_inset Formula $R/D$
\end_inset

 is the reserve ratio.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The money market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
quantity of money demanded
\series default
 is the amount we want to hold on to.
 It is influenced by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Price level: The more expensive things are, the more money we hold onto
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Nominal interest rate: The more we can make by investing, the less money
 we hold onto
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Real GDP: The more we spend, the more we must have held onto
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Financial innovation: More convenient means of payment that don't count
 as money means we hold onto less money
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
demand for money
\series default
 is the demand curve between real money demanded and the nominal interest
 rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Short-run equilibrium
\series default
: The 
\series bold
supply of money curve
\series default
 is a vertical line at the supply of real money.
 Their intersection gives you the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equilibrium
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 interest rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Long-run equilibrium
\series default
: When the inflation rate is as expected and real GDP equals potential GDP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quantity theory of money
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It states that increasing the quantity of money eventually increases the
 price level proportionally.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
velocity of circulation
\series default
 is the average number of times each dollar is used (to buy GDP components)
 per year.
 It is given by the 
\series bold
equation of exchange
\series default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MV=GDP=PY
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the price level, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is the real GDP, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the quantity of money.
 Expressing this in terms of rates gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{Inflation rate}= & \phantom{+}\text{Money growth rate}\\
 & +\text{Rate of velocity change}\\
 & -\text{Real GDP growth rate}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the rate of velocity change is approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

