exports effect
\series default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Interest rates for that currency vs.
 others
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The expected future exchange rate (the 
\series bold
expected profit effect
\series default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The supply for a currency is influenced by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The exchange rate itself
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Our demand for their imports (the 
\series bold
imports effect
\series default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Interest rates for that currency vs.
 others
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The expected future exchange rate (the 
\series bold
expected profit effect
\series default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When interest rates differ between currencies, there is an 
\series bold
interest rate differential
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
People doing 
\series bold
arbitrage
\series default
 achieve four outcomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
The law of one price
\series default
: The price of a thing is the same everywhere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
No round-trip profit
\series default
: You can't make money by trading in a cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Interest rate parity
\series default
: The risk free rate is the same for all currencies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Purchasing power parity
\series default
: The price of a thing is the same in all currencies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Speculation
\series default
 is, to massively generalize, +EV trading.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
real exchange rate
\series default
 is the relative price of goods between two countries.
\family typewriter

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
RER=EP/P'
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Exchange rate policy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
flexible exchange rate
\series default
 is determined fully by the forex market.
 A 
\series bold
fixed exchange rate
\series default
 is fixed by a government via active intervention, usually by burning their
 foreign reserves or printing money.
 A 
\series bold
crawling peg
\series default
 is a peg that changes over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Financing international trade
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A country's 
\series bold
balance of payments accounts
\series default
 records its international trading, borrowing, and lending.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
current account
\series default
 is exports minus imports, minus net interest and net transfers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
capital and financial account
\series default
 is foreign investment in Canada, minus Canadian investment abroad.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
official settlements account
\series default
 is the negative change in 
\series bold
Canadian official reserves
\series default
 (foreign reserves).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total is zero.
 A 
\series bold
net borrower
\series default
 is a country that is borrowing more than it's lending, and a 
\series bold
net lender
\series default
 is not.
 The global loanable funds market has supply and demand curves much like
 those on the level of a single country.
 A 
\series bold
debtor nation
\series default
 has borrowed more than it has lent.
 A 
\series bold
creditor nation
\series default
 has not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Table 25.2) With 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 exports, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 imports, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 government expenditure, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 net taxes, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 investment, and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 savings, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{Net exports} & =X-M\\
\text{Government sector} & =T-G\\
\text{Private sector} & =S-I\\
X-M & =(T-G)+(S-I)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

A short term change in the nominal exchange rate doesn't change the real
 exchange rate.
\end_layout

